com.cyc.kb.wrapper

Class KbObjectWrapper

  • java.lang.Object
    • com.cyc.kb.wrapper.KbObjectWrapper
  • All Implemented Interfaces:
    KbObject
    Direct Known Subclasses:
    AssertionWrapper, KbTermWrapper, SentenceWrapper, SymbolWrapper, VariableWrapper

    public abstract class KbObjectWrapper
extends Object
implements KbObject
    An abstract base class for implementing KbObjects per the decorator pattern. To use, extend this class and implement the wrapped() method to return the wrapped object.

      • isIndexical

        public boolean isIndexical()
                    throws SessionCommunicationException
        Description copied from interface: KbObject
        Is this object an indexical? I.e., it is an instance of #$IndexicalConcept?

        Indexicals are those terms which depend upon the occasion of use or the user. For example, consider words such as "I", "Now", or "Here". When I use the word "I," I am referring to myself, but when you use the word "I", you are referring to yourself. Similarly, "Now" denotes the moment in which the word is used, and "Here" refers to the location at which the word is used.

        An entity which is referenced by an indexical is known as a referent. For example, the referent of "Here" could be France, the City of Austin, the room that we're currently in, or whatever else the geographical context might be when the word is used. (See #$indexicalReferent in the Cyc KB.) The process of determining the referent for an indexical is known as resolving the indexical.

        Some indexicals can be resolved automatically by Cyc; for example, Cyc can automatically resolve #$Now-Indexical to the current time, #$TheUser to the current Cyclist (per SessionOptions.getCyclistName(), or #$TheCurrentHostName to the hostname of the Cyc server. Other indexicals must be ultimately resolved somehow by the external application; for example, Cyc doesn't have any rules for resolving an indexical like (TheNamedFn InformationStore "data source").

        In the case of queries, all of the indexicals in a query's sentence and context must be resolved in order for the query to be run. Cyc will handle any automatically resolvable indexicals (such as #$Now-Indexical), but all other indexicals must be resolved by the application; for example, (TheNamedFn InformationStore "data source") would need to be replaced with a specific instance of #$InformationStore. This can be accomplished by adding substitutions to a Query; for more information, see com.cyc.query.QuerySpecification#setSubstitutions(java.util.Map) .

        Specified by:
        isIndexical in interface KbObject
        Returns:
        whether the object is an indexical
        Throws:
        SessionCommunicationException - if there is a problem communicating with Cyc
        See Also:
        KbObject.resolveIndexical(), KbTerm.replaceTerms(java.util.Map), Sentence.getIndexicals(boolean), Sentence.replaceTerms(java.util.Map), com.cyc.query.QuerySpecification#setSubstitutions(java.util.Map), com.cyc.query.QuerySpecification#addSubstitutions(java.util.Map), QuerySpecification.getSubstitutions()

      • quote

        public KbIndividual quote()
                   throws KbTypeException,
                          CreateException
        Description copied from interface: KbObject
        Returns a quoted version of this object. E.g., this method would return (#$Quote #$Plato) from #$Plato. This method does not modify the original KbObject, but instead returns a new KbObject. Calling this method on a quoted object will return a quoted object which is nested one level deeper; e.g., this method would return (#$Quote (#$Quote #$Plato)) from (#$Quote #$Plato). For a version of this method which won't further nest quoted objects, see KbObject.toQuoted().

        See KbObject.isQuoted() for more details about quoted objects.

      • unquote

        public <O> O unquote()
              throws KbTypeException,
                     CreateException
        Description copied from interface: KbObject
        Returns the object referred to by a quoted object. E.g., this method would return #$Plato from (#$Quote #$Plato). This method does not modify the original KbObject, but instead returns a new object. This method will only remove one level of quoting; e.g., it would return (#$Quote #$Plato) from (#$Quote (#$Quote #$Plato)). If the object is not quoted, a KbTypeException will be thrown. For a version of this method which won't throw an exception for an unquoted object, and which will fully unquote nested quotes, see KbObject.toUnquoted().

        See KbObject.isQuoted() for more details about quoted objects.

      • toQuoted

        public KbIndividual toQuoted()
                      throws KbTypeException,
                             CreateException
        Description copied from interface: KbObject
        Returns a quoted version of this object. This method is similar to KbObject.quote(), but will return a reference to itself if the object is already quoted (as opposed to returning a nested version of the quoted object). E.g., this method would return (#$Quote #$Plato) from either #$Plato or (#$Quote #$Plato). This method does not modify the original KbObject, but instead returns a new KbObject (or a reference to itself, if it's already quoted.)

        See KbObject.isQuoted() for more details about quoted objects.

        Specified by:
        toQuoted in interface KbObject
        Returns:
        the quoted version of this object, or this object if it is already quoted

This method does not modify the original KbObject, but instead returns a new object (or a reference to itself, if it's already fully unquoted.)

      • possiblyResolveIndexical

        public <O> O possiblyResolveIndexical(Map<KbObject,Object> substitutions)
                               throws SessionCommunicationException,
                                      KbTypeException
        Description copied from interface: KbObject
        Attempts to resolve the object from a substitutions map. If the object is an indexical and has a referent specified in the substitutions map, this method will return the referent object from the substitutions map; if the original object is not an indexical, it will simply return itself. Note that this method will not attempt to do any automatic resolution; see KbObject.resolveIndexical() if you need that.

        This method is specifically intended to be called in large batch operations where some KbObjects may be indexicals and others may not, and to be chained with other methods like KbTerm.replaceTerms(java.util.Map), so it attempts to be a little more forgiving than #resolveIndexical(). For this reason, it will not throw an exception simply because the original object is not an indexical. However, it will throw an exception under any of the following conditions:

        • The object is not an indexical, but a referent is found in the substitutions map.
        • The object is an indexical which cannot be automatically resolved, and no referent is found in the substitutions map.
        • The referent provided by the substitutions map is the same as the original object.
        • The referent is not of the expected type.

        For a brief overview of indexicals, see KbObject.isIndexical().

        Specified by:
        possiblyResolveIndexical in interface KbObject
        Type Parameters:
        O - the referent's expected type
        Parameters:
        substitutions - the substitutions map
        Returns:
        the object's referent, or the object itself (if not an indexical)
        Throws:
        SessionCommunicationException - if there is a problem communicating with Cyc
        KbTypeException - if the referent is not of the expected type
        See Also:
        KbObject.resolveIndexical()

      • resolveIndexical

        public <O> O resolveIndexical()
                       throws SessionCommunicationException,
                              KbTypeException,
                              CreateException
        Description copied from interface: KbObject
        If the object is an indexical, attempt to resolve it and return the appropriate referent. For example, if called on #$Now-Indexical, this method would return the current date and time. This method does not modify the original KbObject, but instead returns a new KbObject. If the indexical cannot be automatically resolved, or if the KbObject is not an indexical, an exception will be thrown.

        For a brief overview of indexicals, see KbObject.isIndexical().

        Specified by:
        resolveIndexical in interface KbObject
        Type Parameters:
        O - the referent's expected type
        Returns:
        the indexical's referent for the current context
        Throws:
        SessionCommunicationException - if there is a problem communicating with Cyc
        KbTypeException - if the object is not an indexical
        CreateException
        See Also:
        KbObject.possiblyResolveIndexical(java.util.Map)

      • equalsSemantically

        public boolean equalsSemantically(Object object)
        Description copied from interface: KbObject
        Does this represent the same object in the KB as object. This can return true even if the two objects being compared are of different classes, as long as they represent the same object in the KB. Ideally if factory methods are used to create KB API objects, it will ensure that the object returned will be of the tightest subclass possible, so object comparisons will work even when cast to super.
